05162nam a22010095i 9780814768631DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20022002nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147686317 a10.18574/nyu/97808147686312doi  a(DE-B1597)547905  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF4772 .P 7aPOL0220002bisacsh04a342.7308531 aPassavant, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNo Escape :bFreedom of Speech and the Paradox of Rights /cPaul Passavant. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Freedom of Speech and the Paradox of Rights -- t1 Liberal Legal Rights and the Grounds of Nationalism -- t2 John Burgess Is to Woodrow Wilson as Individual Rights Are to Community? Nation, Race, and the Right of Free Speech -- t3 A Moral Geography of Liberty: john Stuart Mill and American Free Speech Discourse -- t4 The Landscape of Rights Claiming: The Shift to a Post-Cold War American National Formation -- t5 Whose First Amendment Is It, Anyway? -- t6 The Governmentality of Discussion -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConventional legal and political scholarship places liberalism, which promotes and defends individual legal rights, in direct opposition to communitarianism, which focuses on the greater good of the social group. According to this mode of thought, liberals value legal rights for precisely the same reason that communitarians seek to limit their scope: they privilege the individual over the community. However, could it be that liberalism is not antithetical to social group identities like nationalism as is traditionally understood? Is it possible that those who assert liberal rights might even strengthen aspects of nationalism? No Escape argues that this is exactly the case, beginning with the observation that, paradoxical as it might seem, liberalism and nationalism have historically coincided in the United States. No Escape proves that liberal government and nationalism can mutually reinforce each other, taking as its example a preeminent and seemingly universal liberal legal right, freedom of speech, and illustrating how it can function in a way that actually reproduces nationally exclusive conditions of power. No Escape boldly re-evaluates the relationship between liberal rights and the community at a time when the call has gone out for the nation to defend the freedom to live our way of life. Passavant challenges us to reconsider traditional modes of thought, providing a fresh perspective on seemingly intransigent political and legal debates.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aFreedom of speechxHistoryxUnited States. 0aFreedom of speechzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Constitutions.2bisacsh  aEscape.  aPassavant.  abetween.  aboldly.  acall.  achallenges.  acommunity.  adebates.  adefend.  afreedom.  afresh.  agone.  aintransigent.  alegal.  aliberal.  alife.  alive.  amodes.  anation.  aperspective.  apolitical.  aproviding.  are-evaluates.  areconsider.  arelationship.  arights.  aseemingly.  athought.  atime.  atraditional.  awhen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768631423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814768631/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKA